Initial development log — dictate-daemon
Session date: 2026-05-09
Reconstructed from memory by Claude (Opus 4.7); not a verbatim transcript.

Goal: hands-free dictation into vim (and any focused window) on Kubuntu 24.04
with KDE Plasma 5, X11 session, RTX 5080, Poly Studio P15 mic.


# 1. Picking the approach

User started with a question: "what voice-to-text options do I have on Linux,
ideally I'd like to dictate into vim?"

I surveyed the landscape:
  - nerd-dictation (VOSK, offline, low-latency, types via xdotool/ydotool/wtype)
  - Whisper-based hotkey scripts (whisper.cpp / faster-whisper, push-to-talk)
  - Speech Note (Flatpak, GUI, multiple engines)
  - Talon Voice (powerful, voice-coding, steeper curve)
  - Numen (voice mouse/keyboard control)

Recommended faster-whisper + push-to-talk + xdotool:
  - Best accuracy, especially for technical vocabulary
  - User has RTX 5080 → near-instant inference even on large-v3
  - Simple toggle UX
  - X11 session ($XDG_SESSION_TYPE=x11) → xdotool works without ydotool/uinput
    permissions hassle

User said yes, sketch one.


# 2. Architecture decision: daemon, not one-shot

I sketched a daemon-based design rather than per-invocation:

  - Loading even small.en takes ~1s; large-v3 several seconds.
  - Per-invocation = paying that latency every time → bad UX.
  - Daemon holds the model in GPU memory; toggle is just a FIFO write.

Components:
  - dictate-daemon — Python long-running process, listens on /tmp/dictate.fifo
  - dictate-toggle — trivial bash, writes "toggle" to the FIFO
  - systemd user unit — keeps the daemon running across logins
  - KDE custom shortcut → runs the toggle

Recording via arecord (S16_LE, 16 kHz, mono) — Whisper's expected format.
Typing via xdotool type into the focused window.

Initial environment check:
  - xdotool: missing → would need apt install
  - faster-whisper: missing → would need pip install
  - arecord: present
  - python3: present
  - GPU: visible via nvidia-smi (driver 595.58.03)
  - ~/bin: symlink into ~/src/dotfiles/bin/


# 3. Install script

User asked for an install script. I created three files in ~/src/dotfiles/bin/
(matching the existing setup-csharp-lsp pattern):

  - dictate-daemon (Python, the long-running service)
  - dictate-toggle (bash, the FIFO writer)
  - setup-dictation (bash, idempotent installer)

The installer:
  - apt installs xdotool + python3-venv (sudo)
  - creates a dedicated venv at ~/.local/share/dictate/venv
    (sidesteps PEP 668 pip-restriction on Ubuntu 24.04)
  - pip installs faster-whisper into the venv
  - writes ~/.config/systemd/user/dictate.service inline (heredoc — single source
    of truth, no fourth file to manage)
  - daemon-reload + enable + start
  - verifies "is-active"

User then said: "let's create a dictate-daemon folder for it instead of straight
in bin/."

Reorganized:
  ~/src/dotfiles/dictate-daemon/
    daemon         (renamed from dictate-daemon)
    toggle         (renamed from dictate-toggle)
    setup          (renamed from setup-dictation)

Setup script updated to symlink toggle into ~/bin/ as `dictate-toggle` so KDE
can find it on PATH; systemd ExecStart points at the absolute path of daemon
inside the dotfiles folder.


# 4. Hotkey binding

User ran ./setup themselves successfully. Asked me to bind Meta+H.

KDE Plasma 5 stores custom shortcuts in ~/.config/khotkeysrc. The format is
multi-section INI: a top-level [Data] with DataCount, then [Data_N] groups
(ACTION_DATA_GROUP), and inside those [Data_N_M] entries (SIMPLE_ACTION_DATA)
with Actions / Triggers sub-sections.

Backed up khotkeysrc, added a Data_4 group ("User Shortcuts") with Data_4_1
binding Meta+H to dictate-toggle, bumped [Data] DataCount from 3 to 4.

Reloaded khotkeys via:
  qdbus org.kde.kded5 /kded unloadModule khotkeys
  qdbus org.kde.kded5 /kded loadModule khotkeys

KDE then rewrote khotkeysrc, alphabetically reorganizing sections — my Data_4
ended up around line 996 instead of immediately after Data_3, but the binding
worked structurally.


# 5. Bug 1: Meta+H opens a browser searching "dictate-toggle"

khotkeys' CommandURL field, when given a bare token like "dictate-toggle",
hands it to the URL handler which falls through to a browser web search rather
than executing it. The binding was "working" (mic icon appeared) — wait, no,
that was after the next fix. Initial state: opens Vivaldi searching for
"dictate-toggle".

khotkeys at session-start time has whatever PATH was inherited from login,
which apparently doesn't include ~/bin (or it does but CommandURL prefers URL
interpretation for bare names without a path).

Fix: change CommandURL to absolute path:
  CommandURL=/home/ack/src/dotfiles/dictate-daemon/toggle


# 6. Bug 2: Mic icon appears, but nothing is typed

Pressed Meta+H, KDE toolbar showed "PipeWire ALSA microphone" — capture was
happening. But after stopping, nothing typed.

User asked: is "PipeWire ALSA microphone" the wrong device? (Default source
is the Poly Studio P15 — that's correct, it's their primary input.)

User also asked: Vivaldi has the mic open, is that a problem? Answer: no, on
PipeWire multiple readers can share a source.

The real issue was in the daemon log:

  error: Library libcublas.so.12 is not found or cannot be loaded

CTranslate2 (faster-whisper's backend) needs cuBLAS at runtime but the wheel
doesn't bundle it. The system had only the NVIDIA driver — no CUDA toolkit, no
cuBLAS, no cuDNN.

Fix attempt 1: pip install nvidia-cublas-cu12 nvidia-cudnn-cu12==9.* into the
venv. I assumed CTranslate2's wheel rpath would find them. **Wrong.** The
restart appeared to succeed (no error in immediate logs) but only because my
test sent two toggles back-to-back with no audio — VAD short-circuited and the
GPU code never ran. As soon as user spoke, cuBLAS error returned.

Fix attempt 2: set LD_LIBRARY_PATH in the systemd unit:

  Environment=LD_LIBRARY_PATH=<venv>/.../nvidia/cublas/lib:<venv>/.../nvidia/cudnn/lib

This worked. Updated setup script to find these lib dirs dynamically and write
them into the unit, so a fresh install does the right thing automatically.

Lesson: if a "fix" only validates against an empty/silent test, it's not
validated.


# 7. Real-time vs batch

User got transcription working but noticed it only types after stopping the
recording, not in real time. Asked if that's expected.

Yes, by design. Tradeoffs explained:
  - Batch (current): Whisper sees the whole utterance → best punctuation,
    capitalization, contractions; faster overall.
  - Streaming: words appear as you speak; worse punctuation, occasional
    mid-sentence rewrites; needs LocalAgreement-style hypothesis confirmation.

User wanted both modes:
  - Meta+H = batch (transcribe on stop)
  - Meta+Shift+H = streaming (live-ish typing)

Implemented streaming via:
  - arecord -t raw - (S16LE to stdout pipe instead of WAV file)
  - background thread reads ~100ms chunks, appends to a rolling bytearray
  - every STREAM_STEP_SEC (1.5s) re-transcribe the whole buffer
  - LocalAgreement-2: words that match the previous hypothesis are "confirmed"
  - type only words newly confirmed since last commit, prepended with a space
  - cap buffer at STREAM_WINDOW_SEC (30s); if exceeded, force-commit current
    hypothesis and reset (acceptable context boundary at natural pauses)
  - beam_size=1, condition_on_previous_text=False for each iter
    (faster + more deterministic for stability)

Added second toggle script (stream-toggle), second symlink (~/bin/dictate-stream-toggle),
second hotkey (Meta+Shift+H → Data_4_2 in khotkeysrc, bumped Data_4 DataCount to 2).


# 8. Universal stop

User: "is it possible to have meta+h to toggle off regardless of the scenario
since I won't be running them in parallel?"

Refactored Dictator.toggle_batch / toggle_stream to share a _stop_active()
helper. New behavior: either hotkey stops whatever's active; differs only
when starting from idle (Meta+H starts batch, Meta+Shift+H starts stream).


# 9. Streaming final-flush bug

User: "if I stop streaming now it doesn't catch up to what the last bits I have
said prior to hitting stop."

Bug in StreamSession._commit's force-flush path: it used
`confirmed.startswith(self.committed)` to decide what new text to type. But
Whisper's full-buffer transcription on stop often slightly differs from the
incremental output (capitalizes the first word of a sentence, adds a trailing
period, etc.) — so the startswith check fails and the tail gets dropped.

Fix: on force flush, switch to word-count semantics. Trust the word count of
already-typed text; append everything beyond that, even if Whisper rewrote
the prefix.


# 10. Bug 3: stopping dictation locks the screen (twice)

The most painful one. User reported lock screen freezing twice, on Meta+H
press to stop dictation. Second time the lock greeter hung — no password
prompt, frozen clock.

Recovered the hung lock from this shell:
  loginctl unlock-session 3        # didn't take, greeter was hung
  kill -9 <kscreenlocker_greet>    # cleared it; LockedHint went to no

Then investigated. Pulled the journal:

  $ grep "Lock" ~/.config/kglobalshortcutsrc
  Lock Session=Meta+L\tScreensaver,Meta+L\tScreensaver,Lock Session

That's the smoking gun. The race:
  1. User presses Meta+H to stop dictation (~50ms hold)
  2. khotkeys fires immediately → script writes to FIFO
  3. Daemon stops the session and transcribes (100ms–1s for streaming flush)
  4. xdotool starts typing the result
  5. User's finger is *still releasing Meta* during step 4 sometimes
  6. xdotool types an 'l' or 'L' (very common in English text)
  7. KWin sees fresh Meta+L event → fires Lock Session
  8. kscreenlocker_greet sometimes gets confused by the burst typing → hangs

Fix: --clearmodifiers on xdotool type. This temporarily releases all held
modifiers before each keystroke, then re-presses any that were active.

  subprocess.run(["xdotool", "type", "--clearmodifiers", "--delay", "1", "--", text])

Also bumped --delay from 0 to 1 so we're not slamming the X server.

Saved this gotcha as a feedback memory: any future xdotool scripting on this
workstation must use --clearmodifiers, because Meta+L is the lock shortcut.


# Final state of the system

Files in ~/src/dotfiles/dictate-daemon/:
  daemon                      — Python service, batch + stream modes
  toggle                      — writes "toggle" to FIFO
  stream-toggle               — writes "stream-toggle" to FIFO
  setup                       — idempotent installer
  initial-development.log     — this file

Symlinks in ~/bin/:
  dictate-toggle              → dictate-daemon/toggle
  dictate-stream-toggle       → dictate-daemon/stream-toggle

Venv at ~/.local/share/dictate/venv with:
  faster-whisper, nvidia-cublas-cu12, nvidia-cudnn-cu12==9.*

Systemd unit at ~/.config/systemd/user/dictate.service:
  - LD_LIBRARY_PATH set to the venv's nvidia/cublas/lib and nvidia/cudnn/lib
  - ExecStart launches the venv's python on the daemon

KDE shortcuts in ~/.config/khotkeysrc Data_4 group:
  - Data_4_1: Meta+H → /home/ack/src/dotfiles/dictate-daemon/toggle
  - Data_4_2: Meta+Shift+H → /home/ack/src/dotfiles/dictate-daemon/stream-toggle


# Behavior summary

  Idle → Meta+H starts batch; Meta+Shift+H starts streaming.
  Anything active → either hotkey stops it (universal stop).

Batch:
  - Records to a temp WAV until next toggle.
  - On stop: transcribe whole file, type result.
  - Best for prose; latency = inference time (~sub-second on 5080).

Streaming:
  - Audio piped from arecord into Python every 100ms.
  - Every 1.5s: re-transcribe full rolling buffer (capped at 30s).
  - LocalAgreement-2 marks words confirmed; new confirmed words are typed.
  - On stop: full-buffer transcribe; type any uncommitted words by word-count.
  - Latency per word: 1.5–3s; punctuation/casing slightly worse than batch.


# Lessons / things I'd do differently next time

  1. Validate fixes against the *actual* failure path, not a degenerate test
     case. The cuBLAS "fix" looked good only because empty audio bypassed CUDA.

  2. On X11, ALWAYS use xdotool --clearmodifiers when typing after a hotkey
     trigger. The Meta+L lock collision is the obvious one but other Meta-bound
     shortcuts have the same risk.

  3. khotkeysrc CommandURL needs an absolute path — bare names go through URL
     handler which falls through to web search.

  4. CTranslate2 / faster-whisper does not auto-find pip-installed CUDA libs
     via rpath in 4.x; LD_LIBRARY_PATH must be set explicitly in the systemd
     unit (or some other env mechanism).

  5. For dedicated Python services on Ubuntu 24.04, a per-service venv beats
     fighting PEP 668. Tiny inconvenience; large robustness gain.
